featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
First, it is important to clarify what is the location of the mosque. What is the status and importance of the mosque? When it will be known, what is the status of the mosque in the eyes of Allah and His Messenger? Then, God willing, building a mosque, decorating it, settling it, will become easy, and then it will be easy to carry it out keeping in mind the importance of its requirement.
A mosque is a sacred place where God is worshipped, remembered, the most blessed parts of the earth, the best parts, the most precious parts, they are known as mosques. are; So it comes in a hadith:
"Hazrat Abu Huraira (may Allah be pleased with him) narrates that the Messenger of Allah, may God bless him and grant him peace, said that the most favorite places in cities with Allah are their mosques, and the most disliked places in cities are their markets." (Narrated by Muslim)
Similarly, in another hadith: Khairu al-Amakin-Masajiduhha wa Sharr-ul-Amakin-Iswaqhuha. "In the best places of the earth are mosques and in the worst places are markets."
These blessed hadiths prove that the most blessed and holy place on earth is the mosque; Therefore, who would not be aware of the importance of Masjid Haram, they pray towards it at all five times in the morning and evening, there is the Kaaba of Allah, every year pilgrims go there, do Tawaf and enjoy the spiritual enjoyment of Masjid Haram.
Allah created the Kaaba as the first and holiest place on earth. The limited part of its sides and sides is called Masjid Haram. Today, all the mosques of the whole world are the cover of Masjid Haram, this is the reason that it is mentioned in a hadith that the greatest reward is Masjid Haram.
Hazrat Anas (may Allah be pleased with him) narrates that the Messenger of Allah (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) said: The prayer that a man prays in his house is only one prayer, and the prayer that he prays in the mosque of his neighborhood is equal to twenty-five prayers. The prayer he offered in the Jama Masjid is equal to five hundred prayers, and the prayer he offered in the Al-Aqsa Mosque (Bait al-Maqdis) is equal to fifty thousand prayers, and the prayer he offered in my mosque (Prophet's Mosque). He is also equal to fifty thousand prayers, and the prayer he performed in Masjid al-Haram (Makkah al-Mukarmah) is equal to one hundred thousand prayers. (Ibn Majah)
May Allah bless everyone with gratitude.
A worshiper is a guest of Allah: When a servant of Allah comes to the mosque and prays, then he has fulfilled a duty, but it is strange that Allah honors the person who comes to his house, gives him a feast, because the mosque belongs to Allah. There is a house, and the householder is the host, and the visitor is the guest; Thus, there is a hadith: "Hazrat Abu Huraira (RA) narrated that the Messenger of Allah (PBUH) said, "Whoever goes to the mosque in the morning or in the evening, Allah will prepare his hospitality whenever he goes." , in the morning or in the evening". (Agreed)
Guests also have ranks: And not only that, but Allah has ranks and ranks of guests, some people come from far away, some come very close. Some come to the mosque much earlier, some come much later. The ranks and ranks of all of them are based on the same calculation, so it is mentioned in the hadith: "Hazrat Abu Musa (RA) narrates that the Messenger of Allah (PBUH) said, "The person who is the highest among people in terms of the reward of prayer is he. He is the one who is the farthest among them, the one who has to walk the longest, and the person who stays for the prayer, even if he prays with the Imam, his rank is greater in terms of reward than the person who does not pray. Pray and sleep."
The mosque is the Islamic center of the entire ummah: these few hadiths and traditions that have been presented make the position and status of the mosque very clear and there is a large collection of hadiths on this subject. And why not, the house of Allah is the religious, Islamic and spiritual center of the entire Ummah. There the hearts are warmed by the remembrance of Allah. The fire of knowledge and truth is lit in the breasts. There, vows and vows of obeying and obeying Allah are made, begs are asked for mercy and forgiveness from the Lord of the worlds, and fear and indignation are expressed before the glory of the creator and the house.
This house of Allah is the backbone of the Muslim Ummah and the religion of Islam. Collectiveness and collective strength are based in the mosque, mutual love and brotherhood and sharing in each other's pains and sufferings come from here.
